      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Fluid &amp; weight between sessions</h1>
      <p class="lead">Every kilogram of fluid you gain between sessions puts extra strain on your heart. The good news: with a few daily habits, this is one of the most controllable parts of dialysis. Here's how to stay safe.</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>Why fluid builds up between sessions</h2>
      <p>Healthy kidneys remove extra fluid continuously — every hour, every day. On dialysis, that
      job pauses between treatments. So everything you drink, plus the water hidden inside food,
      slowly accumulates until your next session. Many Filipino dialysis patients gain
      <strong>2–4 kg</strong> of fluid between sessions.</p>
      <p>That fluid does not just sit quietly. It raises your blood pressure, fills your blood
      vessels, makes your heart work harder, and — if it builds up too much — can back up into your
      lungs. This is why managing fluid is not about willpower or punishment. It is about protecting
      your heart.</p>

      <h2>The weekend gap — why Monday is the risky day</h2>
      <p>On a typical Monday–Wednesday–Friday schedule, the gap from Friday to Monday is
      <strong>three days</strong> — the longest stretch without dialysis all week. Fluid has more
      time to pile up, and that is exactly when the most dangerous overload happens. Studies show the
      highest rate of dialysis-related heart events happens on <strong>Monday</strong>, the first
      session after the weekend.</p>
      <p>The lesson is simple: <strong>Saturday and Sunday discipline matters most.</strong> Being a
      little stricter with salt and fluid on the weekend does more to protect you than anything else
      you can do.</p>

      <h2>What too much fluid does to your body</h2>
      <p>Understanding the "why" makes the daily habits easier to follow.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Your heart:</strong> extra fluid raises blood pressure and blood volume, forcing
        the heart to pump harder. Over months and years, the heart enlarges and stiffens, which
        raises the risk of serious heart problems.</li>
        <li><strong>Your lungs:</strong> severe overload can flood the lungs (pulmonary edema),
        causing sudden breathlessness, a feeling that you cannot lie flat, and coughing. This is a
        medical emergency.</li>
        <li><strong>The dialysis session itself:</strong> when you arrive with a lot of extra fluid,
        the machine has to pull it off quickly. Fast removal can cause your blood pressure to crash,
        triggering cramps, dizziness, and vomiting. Keeping your gains small keeps each session
        gentler and safer.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What "dry weight" means</h2>
      <p>Your <strong>dry weight</strong> (also called your target weight) is the weight you should
      reach at the <em>end</em> of each session — the weight at which your blood pressure is normal,
      your lungs are clear, and your body carries no excess fluid. Think of it as your true body
      weight without any fluid burden. Every gain between sessions is measured against this number.</p>
      <p>Your dry weight is not fixed forever. If you lose muscle or gain real body weight, it needs
      to be adjusted. Signs it may need rechecking include frequent cramps during dialysis, blood
      pressure that stays low after sessions, or clothes that suddenly feel looser or tighter. Tell
      your care team about these — they set and adjust your dry weight together with you.</p>

      <h2>Salt — the real driver of thirst</h2>
      <p>Most people think fluid overload is simply about drinking too much water. The real driver is
      <strong>salt (sodium)</strong>. Every gram of sodium you eat pulls about <strong>200 mL</strong>
      of water into your body and makes you thirsty. The more salt you eat, the thirstier you feel,
      the more you drink, and the more fluid you retain.</p>
      <p>This is actually encouraging news: cutting back on salty food is the single most effective
      way to make your fluid limit feel comfortable, instead of feeling like constant deprivation. A
      common target is <strong>less than 2,000 mg of sodium a day</strong> — roughly one teaspoon of
      salt, including what is already inside your food. Our renal dietitian can help you reach this
      with real Filipino meals.</p>

      <h2>Salt in everyday Filipino food</h2>
      <p>Much of the salt we eat is hidden in condiments and processed food, not in the rice on the
      plate. A few everyday examples:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Patis</strong> — about 1,350 mg of sodium in a single tablespoon (most of a day's
        limit in one spoon).</li>
        <li><strong>Bagoong</strong> — about 480 mg per teaspoon, and easy to overuse.</li>
        <li><strong>Canned sardines</strong> — around 700–900 mg per can; draining and rinsing can cut
        the sodium by about a third.</li>
        <li><strong>Processed cheese</strong> — about 400 mg a slice, hiding in sandwiches and snacks.</li>
        <li><strong>Instant noodle seasoning packets</strong> — one of the saltiest things in the
        kitchen; use only a fraction, or skip it.</li>
        <li><strong>Plain rice</strong> — under 5 mg. Rice itself is not the salt problem.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Hidden fluid you might miss</h2>
      <p>Fluid is not only what you pour into a glass. Watch for these easy-to-forget sources:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Soup and broth</strong> — sabaw counts as fluid. Eat the solids and leave most of
        the broth behind.</li>
        <li><strong>Water-rich fruits</strong> — watermelon, grapes, and oranges are mostly water.
        Enjoy them, but count them.</li>
        <li><strong>Ice, gelatin, and soft frozen treats</strong> — these melt into fluid too.</li>
        <li><strong>IV drips ordered by other doctors</strong> — always tell any doctor or ER that you
        are on dialysis, so they can be careful with fluids given through a vein.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="notice"><strong>A note on "low-salt" substitutes:</strong> many salt substitutes
      replace sodium with potassium, which can be dangerous for dialysis patients. Ask your care team
      before using any salt substitute.</div>

      <h2>Weigh yourself every day</h2>
      <p>Daily weighing is the only early-warning system you have. Weigh yourself at the same time each
      day and compare with your dry weight. If you are already <strong>1.5 kg</strong> above dry weight
      the morning after dialysis, yesterday's intake was too high — and you can adjust today before it
      becomes a problem. If a scale is hard to afford, ask your dialysis center; some can provide one or
      check your weight at each visit.</p>

      <h2>Simple ways to control thirst — without drinking</h2>
      <p>Because thirst comes from salt, the best fixes tame the thirst rather than fighting it with
      water. Try these:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Rinse your mouth with cold water and spit it out instead of swallowing.</li>
        <li>Chew sugar-free gum to keep your mouth moist.</li>
        <li>Suck one small ice cube slowly — it lasts longer and uses less fluid than a drink.</li>
        <li>Choose cold foods over hot ones; cold feels more refreshing.</li>
        <li>Avoid salty snacks — they trigger thirst within minutes.</li>
        <li>Take the salt shaker off the table entirely, so it is out of habit and out of reach.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The pitcher trick — make your limit visible</h2>
      <p>Each morning, fill a pitcher or bottle with the amount of fluid you are allowed that day.
      Every time you drink anything, pour out or remove that same amount. When the container is empty,
      you are done for the day. Seeing the physical amount left is far easier than counting in your
      head — and keeping the pitcher where the whole family can see it turns fluid control into
      something you do together, not alone.</p>

      <h2>Be extra strict before dialysis — especially Sunday</h2>
      <p>The day before dialysis is when a little extra care pays off the most. For a
      Monday–Wednesday–Friday schedule, <strong>Sunday</strong> is the most important day: keep salt
      and fluid to a minimum, and weigh yourself before bed. The day right after dialysis is a good
      day to be strict too, giving yourself a buffer before the next gap.</p>
      <div class="notice"><strong>Do not wait until Monday.</strong> If on Sunday evening you are more
      than <strong>2.5–3 kg</strong> above your dry weight, feel breathless, or cannot lie flat to
      sleep, call your dialysis center that night. It is always better to ask early than to wait.</div>

      <h2>Warning signs of too much fluid</h2>
      <p>Go to the emergency room or call your dialysis center right away if you notice any of these:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Sudden breathlessness, or needing to sit upright to breathe (especially waking at night
        gasping).</li>
        <li>Frothy or pink-tinged sputum when you cough.</li>
        <li>Sudden, severe swelling of the ankles, legs, or face.</li>
        <li>Weight <strong>3 kg or more</strong> above your dry weight at any time.</li>
        <li>Blood pressure above <strong>180/110 mmHg</strong>.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="notice"><strong>Tell us right away</strong> about swelling, breathlessness, or a
      sudden jump in weight or blood pressure. Caught early, fluid overload is very manageable — and
      your care team would always rather hear from you sooner than later.</div>

